2026-04-16 12:26:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Input Cable (+) 6'] hypothesis_explanation='The only anomaly found in the otherwise correct series chain is that Control Input Cable (+) 6 has its negative (return) conductor floating/disconnected, while all other cables maintain both conductors in the daisy‑chain. This means that for Control Module 6 the paired 0 V line that should accompany its incoming +12 V is open, so the module and everything downstream lack a complete circuit reference for current flow. In effect, the positive rail coming into Module 6 has no corresponding return path at that segment, preventing current from reaching the downstream modules and the load lamp. This single open connection in the return path is sufficient to explain: (1) the power‑supply LED being on (it is locally across the battery and unaffected), (2) all control‑module indicator LEDs being off (no complete loop through their series resistors), and (3) the load lamp never turning on, even with all switches closed. Repairing/reconnecting the 0 V conductor associated with Control Input Cable (+) 6 should restore continuity for the entire series chain downstream of Module 6 and resolve the fault.'
